Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Randulf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman given name, Old Norse <i>Rannulfr</i>, derived from <i>rand</i> ‘rim, shield’ (or <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’) + <i>úlfr</i> ‘wolf’."],"variants":[{"name":"Randolph","meanings":["Properly Radolph, the same as the German names Radulph, Radolf, Hroadolf, RudoIph; from Old German rad-ulph, help or counsel. The nickname is Rann."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Randulf DeCharun Roydon was born about 1130, in Roydon, Norfolk, England as the son of Randulf DeCharun. He had at least 1 son with Maud DeMorley. He died about 1196, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1130–about 1196":"umbes 1130–umbes 1196","1130–1196":"1130–1196","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1161–1185":"1161–1185","1075–1159":"1075–1159","1190":"1190","1159":"1159","1135":"1135","after 1185":"pärast 1185","1075":"1075","1185":"1185","1196":"1196","1130":"1130","1161":"1161","about 1130":"umbes 1130","about 1196":"umbes 1196","Roydon, Norfolk, England":"Roydon, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lian Arth Monmouthshire County Wales England, United Kingdom":"Wales, South Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","probably Englan